[[File:Coupling Nut.svg|thumb|A coupling nut and its orthographic view]]

A '''coupling nut''', also known as '''extension nut''', is a [[Screw thread|threaded]] [[fastener]] for joining two male threads, most commonly a [[threaded rod]],<ref name="McMaster-Carr-1">{{cite web|title=Coupling Nuts |work=About Nuts, Materials, and Finishes |publisher=[[McMaster-Carr]] |url=http://www.mcmaster.com/#hex-coupling-nuts/=m1m9ak|accessdate=26 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Extension Nut / Coupling Nut |url=http://www.kisanengineers.com/nuts.html|publisher=Kisan Engineers Machine Tools|website=KisanEngineers.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227100709/http://kisanengineers.com/nuts.html |archivedate=27 December 2011 |deadurl=no}}</ref> but also pipes.<ref>{{Cite book|author=American Railway Master Mechanics' Association |year=1922 |title=Locomotive Cyclopedia of American Practice |edition=sixth|location=New York |publisher=Simmons-Boardman |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=K4YMAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA32 32]}}</ref> The outside of the fastener is usually a hex so a wrench can hold it. Variations include ''reducing coupling nuts'', for joining two different size threads; ''sight hole coupling nuts'', which have a sight hole for observing the amount of [[Engagement (thread)|engagement]]; and coupling nuts with left-handed threads. These are used to make up long rod assemblies from shorter lengths of rods. The rods are threaded into the coupling nut for a certain distance. Coupling nut dimensions are described by the Industrial Fasteners Institute in standard IFI-128. It is given a plain finish. It is either [[cold drawn]] or [[hot rolled]] depending on the [[bar stock]] used. Coupling nuts threaded with two different thread sizes and profiles are called reducing coupling nuts.<ref name="McMaster-Carr-1" />

Coupling nuts can be used to tighten a rod assembly inward or to press a rod assembly outward.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nunn|first=Richard V. |year=1982 |title=Popular Mechanics Guide to Do-It-Yourself Materials |location=New York |publisher=Hearst Books |page=54 |isbn=978-0-87851-150-1}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last1=Olin |first1=L. |last2=Stanland |first2=A. |last3=Allard |first3=F. |chapter=Fiber Optic Hull Penetrators for Submarines |year=1987 |editor=O'Donnell-Leach, Karen |title=Military Applications of Fiber Optics |series=Fiber Optics Reprint Series Volume 14 |location=Brighton, Massachusetts|publisher=Information Gatekeepers Inc. |pages=58–63, page 61 }}</ref>

