{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}
This is a working list of '''Carbon Ranches''' a term referring to [[regenerative agriculture]] practices that specifically accomplish [[carbon sequestration]] in the soil. "The world’s cultivated soils have lost between 50 and 70 percent of their original carbon stock." (Lal<ref>{{cite web|title=Soil as Carbon Storehouse:New Weapon in Climate Fight?|url=https://e360.yale.edu/feature/soil_as_carbon_storehouse_new_weapon_in_climate_fight/2744/ |website=yale.edu|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref>) "A mere two percent increase in the carbon content of the planet’s soils could offset 100 percent of all greenhouse gas emissions going into the atmosphere."(Lal<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Farm Carbon|url=http://www.onenaturellc.com/press/c5isfbpw8tbytnpsdlaw5z3tvh07a5 |website=onenaturellc.com|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref>) Grasslands cover 350 billion hectares, comprising 70% of global agricultural land <ref>{{cite web|title=Challenges and opportunities for carbon sequestration in grassland systems|url=http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/templates/agphome/documents/climate/AGPC_grassland_webversion_19.pdf |website=fao.org|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> making carbon ranching an especially climate beneficial alternative to meat produced as part of a [[Concentrated animal feeding operation]]. Carbon ranching may include, but is not limited to [[Managed intensive rotational grazing]], [[Compost]] application, [[Holistic management (agriculture)]] and [[Tree planting]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Draft Carbon Farm Plan|url=http://www.carboncycle.org/carbon-farming/draft-carbon-farm-plan/ |website=carboncycle.org|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref>
There are many research groups and NGO's studying and advancing this field including Arizona State University,<ref>{{cite web|title= One Million Tons Project (1MMt)|url=https://sustainability.asu.edu/research/project/one-million-tons-project-1mmt/ |website=asu.edu|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> The Carbon Cycle Institute,<ref>{{cite web|title=Carbon Cycle Institute Page|url=http://www.carboncycle.org |website=carboncycle.org|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> [[Holistic Management International]], The Ohio State University,<ref>{{cite web|title=OARDC |url=http://oardc.osu.edu/about/message-director |website=osu.edu|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> The Quivira Coalition,<ref>{{cite web|title=Quivira Coalition |url=http://quiviracoalition.org |website=quiviracoalition.org|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> The Savory Institute,<ref>{{cite web|title=Savory Institute|url=http://savory.global |website=savory.global|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> The Soil Carbon Coalition,<ref name="auto">{{cite web|title=Soil Carbon Change|url=http://soilcarboncoalition.org/changemap.htm |website=soilcarboncoalition.org|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> Texas A&M University.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ranch Management University|url=http://forages.tamu.edu/workshop.html |website=tamu.edu|accessdate=18 Jan 2017}}</ref> This list does not necessarily reflect scientific or academic endorsements insofar as best practices and results vary across ranches, climates, time periods, and sources of funding and are therefore challenging to quantify and/or compare. Currently, confirmation of the carbon ranching designation is confirmed through either third party citation or Soil Organic Matter test result.
